Managers and supervisors are responsible for the following: 



  Maintaining the dignity and respect of persons employed by addressing their workârelated needs without resorting to a formal request for accommodation, to the extent reasonable;

    Satisfying the employerâs legal obligation to accommodate an individualâs needs when they stem from one of the grounds prohibited by the 
    Canadian Human Rights Act
    , up to the point of undue hardship and in a timely manner;

  Providing persons employed with workârelated information, including on employment opportunities, in accessible formats;
  Identifying the resources necessary to fulfill their duty to accommodate in their business and human resources plans; 
  Ensuring that accommodation arrangements are reviewed and updated at least annually;
  Ensuring that persons employed are informed that they have a responsibility to respect the accommodation requirements and privacy of others; 
  Restricting access to any information about an individualâs request for accommodation to the people who have a need to know. The type of information required will depend on the specific facts of each case; 
  Retaining a written record of the accommodation in accordance with relevant information management requirements, when appropriate;
  Ensuring that the needs of individuals who may require accommodation are taken into consideration when planning or designing workârelated processes, events or conferences; and
  Consulting persons employed when there are changes to physical structures, systems or equipment so that the workplace remains barrierâfree.

Persons employed are responsible for the following:



  Informing their manager of their functional limitations or their workârelated needs;
  Providing their manager with the information necessary to identify appropriate accommodation, including information on relevant limitations and restrictions;
  Cooperating and collaborating in good faith with their organizationâs representative(s) to find one or more means to accommodate such needs, taking into consideration issues of health, safety and cost;
  Notifying their manager if their accommodation needs change; and
  Respecting the accommodation requirements and privacy of others.

            These mandatory procedures provide details on the requirements set out in sectionÂ 4 of the 
            Directive on the Duty to Accommodate
            .







Candidates seeking employment



                  With regard to subsectionÂ 4.2, the mandatory procedures for managers when dealing with candidates are as follows:



                      If, after being informed of their right to accommodation under the 
                      Canadian Human Rights Act
                      , a candidate identifies an accommodation need, clarify with the candidate the nature of the barrier and the associated implications;

                    Obtain from the candidate the necessary information and documentation about any limitations or restrictions and, if applicable, any relevant professional assessments or recommendations;
                    Consult appropriate subject matter experts with regard to the accommodation measure(s), if required;
                    Inform the candidate about the proposed accommodation measure(s); and
                    Retain a record of the accommodation requested and provided in the appropriate departmental records.








Persons employed



                  With regard to subsectionÂ 4.2, the mandatory procedures for managers of persons employed are as follows:


                    If a person employed has indicated a work-related need, clarify the nature of the barrier and the associated implications with the person employed;
                    Determine in consultation with the person employed whether the work-related need can be addressed without resorting to a formal request for accommodation, e.g., temporary change in hours of work, alternate work location, no costs associated with solution;
                    Obtain from the person information and documentation about any limitations or restrictions and, if applicable, any relevant professional assessments or recommendations;
                    Request additional information from the individual or obtain the individualâs consent prior to seeking information from a medical practitioner or other relevant third party, in support of a request for accommodation;
                    Consult internal subject matter experts with regard to the accommodation measure(s), including any related implications (e.g., security, technology, financial), if required;
                    Work with employee representatives when accommodation affects other individuals or if the person employed being accommodated requests that employee representatives be consulted;
                    Inform the person about the proposed accommodation measure(s);
                    Provide training to individuals who have been accommodated on the use of any adjusted equipment or systems;
                    Communicate information about the accommodation with the individualâs colleagues only when necessary and only with the consent of the individual;
                    Retain a record of the accommodation requested and provided in the appropriate departmental records; and
                    Allow persons employed to retain technical aids, equipment and support materials if they move to another position in the core public administration and still require that accommodation.
